Step 1: Identify liquid assets that can be used to cover current liabilities. These include:
 • Cash on Hand = 9,383,594.56
 • Bank Deposits = 2,573,984.92
 • Interest Receivable = 23,583.67
 • Accounts Receivable = 6,408,987.07

Step 2: Sum the liquid assets:
 9,383,594.56 + 2,573,984.92 = 11,957,579.48  
 11,957,579.48 + 6,408,987.07 = 18,366,566.55  
 18,366,566.55 + 23,583.67 = 18,390,150.22

Step 3: Identify current liabilities (from the table, end amount is provided):
 Total Current Liabilities = 4,319,436.82

Step 4: Calculate the Quick Ratio:
 Quick Ratio = Total Liquid Assets / Total Current Liabilities  
 Quick Ratio = 18,390,150.22 / 4,319,436.82 ≈ 4.26

Thus, the final answer is:
